snippet.textDisplay: I thought that they were trying to summon an ancient celestial being, with the large statues of mobs as gifts. It explains the alter, as well as the prison cells for sacrifices. The Vindicators are simply followers of the Evokers. The axes were for the murders/maiming/capture of their fellow villagers. I agree with your theory on the ravagers being transformed villlagers. So basically, Evokers worshipped an ancient being, began to gather more followers (The Vindicators), practiced dark magic, murdered and transformed villagers, were banished from the villages, sent out other illagers to create outposts and lead attacks on villagers, while some stayed back in the mansion to bring unto themselves a new leader and new powers, to wipe out those who opposed their power.

snippet.textDisplay:
Okay so, unrelated to the video. I just responded a thread here in the comments about the Wandering Trader and I wanted to share it with you guys.
My theory is that the igloos, the rare structures found in cold biomes, belong to the wandering traders. Here's why:
1. They wear very warm clothes, very closed coats with hoods that hide almost all of their faces. Thus, they came from somewhere cold and distant.
2. They walk along with two llamas. Llamas are native animals from cold biomes and mountain biomes, just like in real life. Why llamas? Why not a mule or a donkey, which can also carry things with them? Because they came from somewhere cold.
3. They use potions to protect themselves by hiding at night and from anything that attacks them. Thus, they are familiar to potion brewing. This explains the potion brewer down beneath the igloos, and the fact that they have the knowledge of how to cure villager zombies.


"But why would they trap those two poor villagers in an igloo's basement?"
i dunno dude, maybe the isolation, nomad life and the cold is driving the trading guy insane lol

snippet.textDisplay:
All zombies drop rotten flesh, so they can’t be made of wool. I personally think that the blue piles of wool are meant to be stand-ins for lapis blocks. Due to the fake wool beds, wool maps, and the Illigers connection to lapis, I think this makes since.

I think the zombies virus was one of the main things that drove away the original builders, and all normal zombies seen in game are just the infected builders. The reason they can’t be cured like infected zombie villagers can is because either A: the cure was made by villagers and designed for them only, or B: the normal zombies have been infected for so long that any hope of curing them will fail. Maybe the normal zombies having seemingly empty eye sockets is some kind of indicator or this, or an effect of some failed attempt at a freaky healing ritual.

snippet.textDisplay:
If the illagers can create life, what's the connection between them and dungeons?
Occasionally, a spider spawner can appear as a room in a woodland mansion, but from what we know, dungeons were introduced before pillagers were, implying that they could have been created by the original 'master builders', or by the pillagers. Because of the choice of a spider spawner, it wouldn't be too far fetched to imply that the illagers built the abandoned mineshafts, or at least filled them with cave spiders. This means that the vanished race of builders built many of the creations we can see in the minecraft world, but the illagers may also have used them at some point. This would allow us to find a complete timeline up to the player spawn.
